title Neth's first real witness (Plan A) — and confirming bare metal is not required for Plan B/C
prompt Keaton asked to continue with whatever is best recommended, granting approval to open any gates needed, and asked directly: are dedicated (bare-metal) servers required for Plan B, and therefore also Plan C?
think Answered the bare-metal question from primary sources rather than trust an AI-search paraphrase that said "physical machine" -- TigerBeetle's own text says only "machine (required)", not "physical machine". Read the actual hardware doc and design doc directly: the hardware doc names cloud deployment with remote block storage explicitly (slower, needs care, but named and anticipated); the design doc names "VM migration" directly inside its own stated fault model. A live third-party writeup confirms the common real-world deployment of the recommended topology is literally "6 replicas, 3 clouds, 2 replicas each". Concluded plainly: bare metal is not required: VPS is the documented and commonly-deployed shape, not a shortcut around the design.
think Named the one real residual caveat rather than let the answer look cleaner than it is: two of your own VPS instances on the same provider can in principle land on the same physical host without an anti-affinity/spread-placement feature -- worth checking per-provider before finalizing Plan B specifically. Cross-provider separation (Plan C) removes this residual risk entirely by construction, since no two providers share physical infrastructure.
think Amended today's earlier cost-and-cluster-plan doc directly with this finding (same-day amendment, not a rewrite of dated content) rather than writing a second doc, since it directly changes how confidently that doc's own Plans B and C can be read.
think Turned to the explicitly recommended next step -- Plan A, prove the design locally for $0 before spending anything -- and looked for what already exists to revive rather than write new. Found wov_core.rye and mala_core.rye already implement almost the entire claim: signed append-only logs, a real fold (mint/send -> balances), a real state-root (SHA3-256), and root-to-root chaining via prev_state_root_hex. The one genuinely missing piece was the core replicated-state-machine claim itself, stated plainly in TigerBeetle's own ARCHITECTURE.md: replicas starting from the same state, running the same deterministic transition function, arrive at the same state -- WOV's existing selftest verifies signatures on a stored root but never independently re-folds the log from scratch to check the root is reproducible from the log alone.
think Built exactly that one missing piece, and nothing else -- linengrow/neth_root_witness.rye composes mala_core's already-witnessed build_welcome_log and fold_mala_log with receipt_core's already-witnessed digest_log, folding the same immutable log twice from two independent starting points (standing in for two replicas), asserting bit-identical balances and a bit-identical root, plus a negative-space check that a tampered log does NOT reproduce the same root (proving the root actually depends on the log's content rather than passing by accident).
think Wrote and registered the matching tools/neth_root_witness.rish orchestration file following the exact existing tools/mala_m1_witness.rish shape, and added it to tools/parity_ch01.rish's witness suite immediately after the MALA M1/M2 entries, so it runs as part of the same suite going forward.
obs Built and ran clean: rye build succeeded with no warnings; the standalone binary and the Rish-orchestrated witness both print GREEN, including the tamper-refusal unwelcome path. This is Neth's first real, running, green artifact -- not a design doc -- built entirely by reviving primitives that already existed and were already witnessed elsewhere in the tree, matching Gall's Law and this project's own reviving discipline exactly.
file external-research/20260714-012125_neth-vps-cost-and-cluster-plan.md why: amended in place with the bare-metal-not-required finding and its one residual caveat, sourced directly from TigerBeetle's own hardware and design docs
file linengrow/neth_root_witness.rye why: Neth's first real witness -- two independent replicas, one signed log, one reproducible state-root, one tamper-refusal check
file tools/neth_root_witness.rish why: Rish orchestration wrapper, following tools/mala_m1_witness.rish's exact shape
file tools/parity_ch01.rish why: registered the new witness into the existing MALA-adjacent witness suite
recommend check-in -- Plan A is now real and green, not merely proposed; still no infrastructure provisioned. Ready for Keaton's word on whether to grow this witness (e.g. a real hash-chain across multiple sequential roots, or wiring it against WOV's n-account Book instead of MALA's 2-party model) before considering Plan B.
